1
00:00:37,178 --> 00:00:39,169
<i>...and I'll tell you what,
the storm system's still moving west.</i>

2
00:00:39,280 --> 00:00:42,272
What are you looking at, Caroline?

3
00:00:43,317 --> 00:00:44,875
The wind, Mom.

4
00:00:47,988 --> 00:00:50,388
They say the hurricane is coming.

5
00:00:52,059 --> 00:00:55,222
I'm on a boat.

6
00:00:55,329 --> 00:00:57,593
I'm drifting.

7
00:00:59,934 --> 00:01:02,232
Can I do anything for you, Mom?

8
00:01:03,604 --> 00:01:05,469
Make anything easier?

9
00:01:06,440 --> 00:01:07,839
Oh, sugar...

10
00:01:08,375 --> 00:01:10,639
There's nothing left to do.

11
00:01:11,145 --> 00:01:12,737
Is what it is.

12
00:01:14,248 --> 00:01:17,217
Finding it harder to keep my eyes open.

13
00:01:19,186 --> 00:01:22,314
My mouth's full of cotton.

14
00:01:22,856 --> 00:01:24,983
There, there, Miss Daisy.

15
00:01:25,092 --> 00:01:27,822
You gonna scratch yourself to ribbons.

16
00:01:32,733 --> 00:01:35,531
Do you want any more
medication, Mother?

17
00:01:36,437 --> 00:01:39,634
Doctor said you could have
as much as you want.

18
00:01:39,740 --> 00:01:42,004
No need for anybody to suffer.

19
00:01:56,991 --> 00:01:59,892
A friend told me
that she never had the chance

20
00:01:59,994 --> 00:02:02,292
to say goodbye to her mother.

21
00:02:05,432 --> 00:02:07,764
- I wanted to...
- It's okay.

22
00:02:07,868 --> 00:02:11,395
I wanted to tell you
how much I'm gonna miss you so...

23
00:02:11,872 --> 00:02:12,964
Mom.

24
00:02:14,975 --> 00:02:16,738
Oh, Caroline.

25
00:02:22,549 --> 00:02:24,039
Are you afraid?

26
00:02:24,151 --> 00:02:25,846
I'm curious.

27
00:02:27,621 --> 00:02:29,248
What comes next?

28
00:02:34,795 --> 00:02:39,562
They built the train station in 1918.

29
00:02:40,601 --> 00:02:43,331
My father was there the day it opened.

30
00:02:45,005 --> 00:02:47,701
He said they had

31
00:02:49,643 --> 00:02:50,940
a tuba band playing.

32
00:02:55,716 --> 00:02:59,777
They had the finest clockmaker
in all of the South

33
00:03:00,387 --> 00:03:03,185
to build that glorious clock.

34
00:03:05,059 --> 00:03:06,617
<i>His name was...</i>

35
00:03:08,529 --> 00:03:10,326
Mr. Gateau.

36
00:03:14,702 --> 00:03:15,862
Mr. Cake.

37
00:03:18,439 --> 00:03:22,603
<i>He was married to a Creole
of Evangeline Parish</i>

38
00:03:22,710 --> 00:03:24,940
<i>and they had a son.</i>

39
00:03:26,880 --> 00:03:31,977
<i>Mr. Gateau was, from birth,
absolutely blind.</i>

40
00:03:34,254 --> 00:03:38,486
<i>When their son was old enough,
he joined the army.</i>

41
00:03:39,426 --> 00:03:43,795
<i>And they prayed God would
keep him out of harm's way.</i>

42
00:03:46,734 --> 00:03:51,467
<i>For months,
he did nothing but work on that clock.</i>

43
00:03:55,542 --> 00:03:56,975
<i>One day,</i>

44
00:03:58,345 --> 00:04:00,245
<i>a letter came.</i>

45
00:04:05,486 --> 00:04:09,217
<i>And Mr. Gateau, done for the night,</i>

46
00:04:09,923 --> 00:04:12,414
<i>went up, alone, to bed.</i>

47
00:04:15,095 --> 00:04:17,893
<i>And their son came home.</i>

48
00:04:23,070 --> 00:04:25,868
<i>They buried him in the family plot,</i>

49
00:04:25,973 --> 00:04:29,875
<i>where he would be with them
when their time came.</i>

50
00:04:31,879 --> 00:04:34,973
<i>Mr. Cake worked on his clock,</i>

51
00:04:37,851 --> 00:04:41,446
<i>laboring to finish.</i>

52
00:04:43,357 --> 00:04:46,690
<i>It was a morning to remember.</i>

53
00:04:47,995 --> 00:04:51,123
<i>Papa said
there were people everywhere.</i>

54
00:04:52,566 --> 00:04:55,126
<i>Even Teddy Roosevelt came.</i>

55
00:05:12,886 --> 00:05:14,751
It's running backwards!

56
00:05:16,390 --> 00:05:18,119
I made it that way

57
00:05:19,726 --> 00:05:21,591
so that perhaps the boys
that we lost in the war

58
00:05:21,695 --> 00:05:23,060
might stand and come home again.

59
00:05:27,968 --> 00:05:29,401
<i>Home to farm,</i>

60
00:05:30,504 --> 00:05:31,698
<i>work,</i>

61
00:05:33,273 --> 00:05:34,968
<i>have children.</i>

62
00:05:38,278 --> 00:05:40,746
<i>To live long, full lives.</i>

63
00:05:43,917 --> 00:05:46,613
Perhaps my own son
might come home again.

64
00:05:55,295 --> 00:05:57,820
I'm sorry if I've offended anybody.

65
00:05:59,399 --> 00:06:01,663
I hope you enjoy my clock.

66
00:06:02,569 --> 00:06:06,437
<i>Mr. Cake was never seen again.</i>

67
00:06:10,811 --> 00:06:15,214
<i>Some say he died of a broken heart.</i>

68
00:06:16,984 --> 00:06:19,248
<i>Some say he went to sea.</i>

69
00:06:24,391 --> 00:06:25,551
Excuse me.

70
00:06:25,659 --> 00:06:28,219
Do you mind if I make a call?
Somebody's watching my little boy.

71
00:06:28,328 --> 00:06:29,556
Sure.

72
00:06:39,806 --> 00:06:42,036
I hope I haven't disappointed you.

73
00:06:42,142 --> 00:06:45,236
You couldn't disappoint me.

74
00:06:46,713 --> 00:06:51,582
Well, I know I don't have much
to show for myself.

75
00:06:54,154 --> 00:06:56,588
Find my dark suitcase.

76
00:07:00,961 --> 00:07:03,862
There's a diary.

77
00:07:06,033 --> 00:07:07,091
This?

78
00:07:09,836 --> 00:07:12,737
Could you read it to me?

79
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:15,538
Is this what you want to do?

80
00:07:15,642 --> 00:07:19,544
I tried to read it
a hundred different times.

81
00:07:20,514 --> 00:07:22,505
Mom, it's not exactly...

82
00:07:22,616 --> 00:07:26,017
It's just the sound of your voice, darling.

83
00:07:26,653 --> 00:07:27,847
Okay.

84
00:07:30,991 --> 00:07:33,960
It's dated April 4th, 1985.

85
00:07:35,095 --> 00:07:37,427
And it says New Orleans.

86
00:07:37,531 --> 00:07:40,261
"This is my last will and testament.

87
00:07:40,367 --> 00:07:44,565
"I don't have much to leave,
few possessions, no money, really.

88
00:07:44,972 --> 00:07:50,205
"I will go out of this world the same way
I came in, alone and with nothing.

89
00:07:50,877 --> 00:07:52,713
"All I have is my story,

90
00:07:52,846 --> 00:07:56,247
"and I'm writing it now
while I still remember it.

91
00:07:57,050 --> 00:08:00,213
"My name is Benjamin.
Benjamin Button. "

92
00:08:00,587 --> 00:08:03,681
<i>And I was born under
unusual circumstances.</i>

93
00:08:04,658 --> 00:08:06,888
<i>The First World War had ended,</i>

94
00:08:07,594 --> 00:08:11,462
<i>and I've been told it was
an especially good night to be born.</i>

95
00:08:13,100 --> 00:08:15,261
Thank God it's over!

96
00:08:15,369 --> 00:08:17,166
We won the war!

97
00:08:32,085 --> 00:08:33,882
The Great War is over!

98
00:08:46,166 --> 00:08:47,190
What are you doing here?

99
00:08:47,300 --> 00:08:48,597
Thomas,

100
00:08:49,836 --> 00:08:51,269
I'm afraid she's going to die.

101
00:08:51,371 --> 00:08:52,531
What?

102
00:08:53,707 --> 00:08:57,336
That's enough.
All of you, get away from her.

103
00:09:00,547 --> 00:09:03,641
I came as quickly as I could.
The streets are filled with people.

104
00:09:03,750 --> 00:09:05,012
Thomas.

105
00:09:05,519 --> 00:09:08,113
Promise me he has a place.

106
00:09:10,524 --> 00:09:11,650
Yeah.

107
00:09:13,026 --> 00:09:15,017
<i>She gave her life for me.</i>

108
00:09:16,063 --> 00:09:19,032
<i>And for that, I am forever grateful.</i>

109
00:09:28,642 --> 00:09:30,041
Mr. Button.

110
00:09:45,358 --> 00:09:46,586
Thomas!

111
00:09:46,693 --> 00:09:47,921
Thomas.

112
00:09:49,930 --> 00:09:52,091
Thomas? Where are you going?

113
00:10:20,727 --> 00:10:23,059
Hey! What are you doing there?

114
00:10:24,297 --> 00:10:26,322
What do you have there?

115
00:11:23,990 --> 00:11:26,322
- Come on, Queenie.
- Now, Mr. Weathers!

116
00:11:26,426 --> 00:11:29,793
Come on, now, you know I ain't got
nothing but work to do around here.

117
00:11:29,896 --> 00:11:32,160
- Come on. Just take some time.
- Stop all this foolishness.

118
00:11:35,368 --> 00:11:37,131
The air is sweet.

119
00:11:41,575 --> 00:11:44,635
You look very handsome tonight,
Miss Queenie.

120
00:11:45,979 --> 00:11:48,106
Handsome as I've ever seen.

121
00:11:49,549 --> 00:11:51,779
The brown matches your eyes.

122
00:11:51,885 --> 00:11:53,216
Oh, hush!

123
00:11:54,688 --> 00:11:58,818
Let's see here.
You ain't no slouch yourself.

124
00:12:07,400 --> 00:12:09,197
Hambert's back in town.

125
00:12:09,302 --> 00:12:13,068
He came home legless, but he's home.

126
00:12:14,074 --> 00:12:16,702
I know you were sweet on him one time.

127
00:12:17,244 --> 00:12:19,109
Sweeter than I should've been.

128
00:12:19,212 --> 00:12:21,112
Miss Simone messed herself.

129
00:12:21,214 --> 00:12:22,442
Oh, sweet Jesus.

130
00:12:22,549 --> 00:12:25,074
She got to stop doing that
or it's diapers for her.

131
00:12:25,185 --> 00:12:27,210
- I'll be right there, Miss Jameson!
- Now, Queenie, now come on.

132
00:12:27,320 --> 00:12:29,880
Okay, Queenie'll be right there.

133
00:12:29,990 --> 00:12:31,252
It's awful nice out here.

134
00:12:31,358 --> 00:12:34,555
Come on out back for a moment.
Take your mind off things.

135
00:12:34,661 --> 00:12:35,685
You're so bad.

136
00:12:35,795 --> 00:12:38,263
- What in God's name?
- What's this?

137
00:12:48,642 --> 00:12:50,872
Oh, the Lord done something here.

138
00:12:50,977 --> 00:12:54,469
Hope I didn't hurt it none
stepping on it like that.

139
00:12:54,581 --> 00:12:56,105
We best leave that for the police.

140
00:12:56,216 --> 00:12:57,706
Poor baby.

141
00:12:58,551 --> 00:12:59,882
I'll go.

142
00:13:00,553 --> 00:13:04,216
It's for sure nobody wanted to keep it.
Come on, baby.

143
00:13:06,893 --> 00:13:09,327
Queenie? Where are you, Queenie?

144
00:13:09,429 --> 00:13:11,363
Hold your water! You go deal with it.

145
00:13:11,464 --> 00:13:13,557
Okay. No, go, I'll be back.

146
00:13:14,434 --> 00:13:17,699
Queenie, Apple, she went and messed
herself all over again!

147
00:13:17,804 --> 00:13:19,669
Jane Childress, start her a bath!

148
00:13:19,773 --> 00:13:21,832
And mind your own business,
Mrs. Duprey.

149
00:13:21,942 --> 00:13:23,739
You'll be messing yourself
soon enough.

150
00:13:23,843 --> 00:13:25,401
Somebody stole my necklace.

151
00:13:25,512 --> 00:13:28,447
Okay. All right, Mrs. Hollister,
I'll be right with you, okay?

152
00:13:28,548 --> 00:13:30,743
Go on back upstairs, hear?

153
00:13:37,057 --> 00:13:39,582
You are as ugly as an old pot

154
00:13:39,693 --> 00:13:41,354
but you're still a child of God.

155
00:13:41,461 --> 00:13:43,827
Queenie, Apple,
she won't take a bath without you!

156
00:13:43,930 --> 00:13:45,397
Mercy.

157
00:13:45,498 --> 00:13:47,466
I'll be right there!

158
00:13:50,503 --> 00:13:53,438
Okay. You just wait right here
for me now, okay?

159
00:13:56,776 --> 00:14:01,406
My sister gave me those pearls.
I can't find them anywhere.

160
00:14:01,514 --> 00:14:05,348
- Somebody's been stealing my jewelry.
- They're right here, Mrs. Hollister. See?

161
00:14:05,452 --> 00:14:08,751
Right around your pretty white neck.
Now, come on. Hush all that noise.

162
00:14:08,855 --> 00:14:11,449
- Is Dr. Rose still here?
- I don't know.

163
00:14:14,260 --> 00:14:15,557
Your heart is strong.

164
00:14:15,662 --> 00:14:18,631
You just want to avoid
any undue stimulation.

165
00:14:19,232 --> 00:14:22,326
I trust you ladies
will help me out with that?

166
00:14:22,435 --> 00:14:25,563
I have something.
Could you come downstairs?

167
00:14:29,275 --> 00:14:32,972
Never seen anything like it.
Nearly blind from cataracts.

168
00:14:33,079 --> 00:14:37,140
I'm not sure if he can hear.
His bones indicate severe arthritis.

169
00:14:37,984 --> 00:14:42,353
His skin has lost all elasticity,
and his hands and feet are ossified.

170
00:14:42,455 --> 00:14:47,051
He shows all the deterioration,
the infirmities, not of a newborn,

171
00:14:47,160 --> 00:14:49,788
but of a man well in his 80s
on his way to the grave.

172
00:14:49,896 --> 00:14:50,885
He's dying?

173
00:14:50,997 --> 00:14:54,228
His body is failing him
before his life's begun.

174
00:14:56,603 --> 00:14:58,036
Where'd he come from?

175
00:14:58,138 --> 00:15:02,507
My sister's child. From Lafayette.
She had an unfortunate adventure.

176
00:15:02,609 --> 00:15:06,511
The poor child, he got the worst of it.
Come out white.

177
00:15:09,549 --> 00:15:14,145
There are places for unwanted babies
like these, Queenie.

178
00:15:14,788 --> 00:15:17,450
No room for another mouth to feed here.

179
00:15:17,557 --> 00:15:20,082
The Nolan Foundation,
despite their good intentions,

180
00:15:20,193 --> 00:15:22,957
thinks this place is
a large nuisance as it is.

181
00:15:23,063 --> 00:15:24,142
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

182
00:15:24,177 --> 00:15:25,222
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

183
00:15:25,331 --> 00:15:29,893
Queenie, some creatures
aren't meant to survive.

184
00:15:33,306 --> 00:15:37,037
No, this baby, he is a miracle.
That's for certain.

185
00:15:37,143 --> 00:15:40,135
Just not the kind of miracle
one hopes to see.

186
00:15:43,183 --> 00:15:45,674
Y'all listen. Y'all listen up here.

187
00:15:46,453 --> 00:15:47,477
We're gonna have us a visitor

188
00:15:47,587 --> 00:15:50,681
that's gonna be staying with us
for a little while.

189
00:15:50,790 --> 00:15:54,487
My sister had a child
and she couldn't see right by it, so...

190
00:15:56,763 --> 00:15:58,492
He's known as...

191
00:16:01,768 --> 00:16:03,065
Benjamin.

192
00:16:03,736 --> 00:16:05,033
Benjamin.

193
00:16:05,939 --> 00:16:08,874
He's not a well child, so we're gonna
have to take good care of him.

194
00:16:08,975 --> 00:16:10,033
I had 10 children.

195
00:16:10,143 --> 00:16:13,476
There's not a baby I can't care for.
Let me see him.

196
00:16:15,682 --> 00:16:19,311
God in Heaven.
He looks just like my ex-husband.

197
00:16:20,153 --> 00:16:22,781
Look, he's prematurely old.

198
00:16:23,289 --> 00:16:26,816
Dr. Rose said he ain't got much more
time on this earth.

199
00:16:27,160 --> 00:16:28,286
Join the club.

200
00:16:33,399 --> 00:16:34,866
He's smiling!

201
00:16:41,641 --> 00:16:44,303
Hambert sends his
remembrances to you.

202
00:16:54,120 --> 00:16:56,452
Are you right out of your mind?

203
00:16:57,757 --> 00:17:01,124
I know you ain't got all the parts
it takes to make one of your own,

204
00:17:01,227 --> 00:17:02,455
but this ain't yours to keep.

205
00:17:02,562 --> 00:17:04,826
It may not even be humankind.

206
00:17:13,973 --> 00:17:16,373
Mr. Weathers, come back here.

207
00:17:18,711 --> 00:17:19,939
Please.

208
00:17:36,296 --> 00:17:38,856
You never know what's coming for you.

209
00:17:48,875 --> 00:17:51,241
<i>It seemed I had found a home.</i>

210
00:17:54,414 --> 00:17:55,472
Is any of this true?

211
00:17:55,582 --> 00:17:58,949
You have such a lovely voice.

212
00:17:59,519 --> 00:18:04,183
Mom, it's an ancient streetcar token.

213
00:18:05,892 --> 00:18:09,020
That clock just kept going,

214
00:18:10,029 --> 00:18:14,227
year after year after year.

215
00:18:18,538 --> 00:18:20,438
<i>But I didn't know I was a child.</i>

216
00:18:20,540 --> 00:18:23,008
Same old crap every day.

217
00:18:23,910 --> 00:18:26,674
<i>I thought I was like everyone else there.</i>

218
00:18:27,680 --> 00:18:29,841
<i>An old man in the twilight of his life.</i>

219
00:18:29,949 --> 00:18:32,281
Could you make him stop that?

220
00:18:33,286 --> 00:18:36,346
Stop banging that fork.
It's used for eating, not for playing with.

221
00:18:36,456 --> 00:18:39,289
And use your napkin, please,
Mr. Benjamin.

222
00:18:41,661 --> 00:18:42,923
Queenie!

223
00:18:55,008 --> 00:18:56,305
Hey, boy.

224
00:19:03,683 --> 00:19:05,981
<i>Always had a healthy curiosity.</i>

225
00:19:07,153 --> 00:19:10,611
<i>What was up the street?
Or around the next corner?</i>

226
00:19:12,492 --> 00:19:13,789
Go get him!

227
00:19:13,893 --> 00:19:17,590
Benjamin! That is dangerous.
Come back over here.

228
00:19:18,331 --> 00:19:20,060
Stay put, child.

229
00:19:22,435 --> 00:19:24,369
<i>I loved her very much.</i>

230
00:19:25,171 --> 00:19:26,798
<i>She was my mother.</i>

231
00:19:26,906 --> 00:19:28,066
Mama.

232
00:19:28,775 --> 00:19:29,901
Mama.

233
00:19:30,710 --> 00:19:34,476
Some days I feel different
than the day before.

234
00:19:35,915 --> 00:19:39,942
Everybody feels different about
themselves, one way or another.

235
00:19:40,920 --> 00:19:43,218
But we're all going the same way.

236
00:19:44,590 --> 00:19:48,253
Just taking different roads to get there,
that's all.

237
00:19:48,361 --> 00:19:50,829
You're on your own road, Benjamin.

238
00:19:53,599 --> 00:19:56,261
Mama? How much longer I got?

239
00:19:56,769 --> 00:20:00,068
Just be thankful
for what you're given, hear?

240
00:20:00,173 --> 00:20:03,233
You're already here longer
than you're supposed to.

241
00:20:06,145 --> 00:20:09,046
<i>Some nights, I'd have to sleep alone.</i>

242
00:20:17,757 --> 00:20:19,418
<i>I didn't mind.</i>

243
00:20:20,326 --> 00:20:23,056
<i>I would listen to the house breathing.</i>

244
00:20:24,263 --> 00:20:26,322
<i>All those people sleeping.</i>

245
00:20:27,800 --> 00:20:29,995
<i>I felt safe.</i>

246
00:20:50,857 --> 00:20:53,451
<i>It was a place of great routine.</i>

247
00:20:53,559 --> 00:20:56,460
<i>Every morning at 5:30,
no matter the weather,</i>

248
00:20:56,562 --> 00:21:00,623
<i>General Winslow, U.S. Army, Retired,
would raise the flag.</i>

249
00:21:03,503 --> 00:21:07,462
<i>Mrs. Sybil Wagner,
once an opera singer of some note,</i>

